# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: hypersaline-lake
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:hypersaline-lake/afar-region] The **Afar Region** (/ˈɑːfɑːr/; Afar: *Qafar Rakaakayak*; Amharic: ዓፋር ክልል), formerly known as **Region 2**, is a regional state in northeastern Ethiopia and the homeland of the Afar people.
[src:hypersaline-lake/afar-region] Its capital is the planned city of Semera, which lies on the paved Awash–Assab highway.
[src:hypersaline-lake/afar-region] It is bordered by Eritrea to the north and Djibouti to the northeast; it also shares regional borders with the Tigray, Amhara, Oromo and Somali regions.
[src:hypersaline-lake/afar-region] The Afar Triangle, the northern part of which is the Danakil Depression, is part of the Great Rift Valley of Ethiopia, and is located in the north of the region.
[src:hypersaline-lake/afar-region] It has the lowest point in Ethiopia and one of the lowest in Africa.
[src:hypersaline-lake/afar-region] The southern part of the region consists of the valley of the Awash River, which empties into a string of lakes along the Djibouti–Ethiopia border.
[src:hypersaline-lake/afar-region] Other notable landmarks include the Awash National Park.
[src:hypersaline-lake/afar-region] Afar Region is a developing region of Ethiopia with a high rate of fertility.
[src:hypersaline-lake/afar-region] Based on the 2024 projections by the Central Statistical Agency of Ethiopia (CSA), the Afar Regional State has a population of 2,120,000, consisting of 1,149,000 men and 971,000 women; urban inhabitants number 504,000 of the population, a further 1,616,000 were pastoralists.
[src:hypersaline-lake/afar-region] Based on the 2007 Census conducted by the Central Statistical Agency of Ethiopia (CSA), the Afar Regional State has a population of 1,290,273, consisting of 575117 men and 715,156 women; urban inhabitants number 249,535 or 13.32% of the population, a further 556,123 or 29.43% were pastoralists.
[src:hypersaline-lake/afar-region] With an estimated area of 96,707 square kilometers, this region has an estimated density of 14.38 people per square kilometer.
[src:hypersaline-lake/afar-region] For the entire region 297,255 households were counted, which results in an average for the Region of 5.6 persons to a household, with urban households having on average 4 and rural households 6 people.
[src:hypersaline-lake/afar-region] In the previous census, conducted in 1994, the region's population was reported to be 1,106,383 of which 626,839 were men and 479,544 women; urban inhabitants were 85,879 or 7.76% of the population.
[src:hypersaline-lake/afar-region] Afar is predominantly (89.96%) spoken in the region and is the working language of the state.
[src:hypersaline-lake/afar-region] Other languages with a significant number of speakers in the state include Amharic (6.83%), Tigrayans (1.06%), Argobba (0.79%), Wolaitta (0.43%), and Oromifa (0.4%).
[src:hypersaline-lake/afar-region] According to the CSA, as of 2004, 48.57% of the total population had access to safe drinking water, of whom 26.89% were rural inhabitants and 78.11% were urban.
[src:hypersaline-lake/afar-region] On 20 April 2007, the regional government announced that it had increased health coverage from 34% to 40%, the result of construction of 64 new health clinics, increasing the total for the region to 111.
[src:hypersaline-lake/afar-region] Afar Depression, Erta Ale active volcano, Awash National Park, Yangudi Rassa National Park, Hadar and Aramis areas, are the major tourist attraction area of the region.
[src:hypersaline-lake/afar-region] The hot springs, Afar culture and cultural games are other attraction areas.
[src:hypersaline-lake/afar-region] In 2005, a giant rift was formed in just a few days.
[src:hypersaline-lake/afar-region] The rift opened when the Dabbahu Volcano, situated in the north of the region, erupted.
[src:hypersaline-lake/afar-region] The crack forming is thought to be part of the process in which the Arabian Plate, the Nubian Plate, and the Somali Plate, are moving apart.
[src:hypersaline-lake/afar-region] This new crack, 500 metres (1,640 ft) long, and 60 metres (197 ft) deep, opened when the lava from the erupting volcano flowed underground and cooled forming a 60 kilometres (37 mi) long, 8 metres (26 ft) wide dike within days.
[src:hypersaline-lake/afar-region] The Afar Depression, a plate tectonic triple junction, is found in the Afar Regional State.
[src:hypersaline-lake/afar-region] This geologic feature is one of Earth's great active volcanic areas.
[src:hypersaline-lake/afar-region] Due to this volcanic activity the floor of the depression is composed of lava, mostly basalt.
[src:hypersaline-lake/afar-region] The continuous process of volcanism results in the occurrence of major minerals, including potash, sulfur, salt, bentonite and gypsum.
[src:hypersaline-lake/afar-region] In addition to these minerals, there are also promising geothermal energy sources and hot springs in different areas of the region.
[src:hypersaline-lake/afar-region] Most of the region's mineral potential are found in Dallol, Berhale and Afdera woredas of Zone Two.
[src:hypersaline-lake/afar-region] Elidar, Dubti and Millee in Zone One, and Gewane in Zone Three, also have some mineral possibilities.
[src:hypersaline-lake/afar-region] Afar is home to peculiar wildlife, which notably include the African wild ass, Grevy's zebra, wild fox, wild cat, cheetah, and ostrich.
[src:hypersaline-lake/afar-region] These wild animals are found in the region's national parks.
[src:hypersaline-lake/afar-region] Because the region's tourism development is still in a poor state there are only two lodges in Awash National Park.
[src:hypersaline-lake/afar-region] As of 2012, the area has been increasingly unstable, as tensions between Ethiopia and Eritrea remain high after the Eritrean–Ethiopian War of 1998 to 2000.
[src:hypersaline-lake/afar-region] On 18 January 2012, five foreign tourists were murdered while on holiday in the region.
[src:hypersaline-lake/afar-region] The Ethiopian government has accused Eritrean gunmen of being responsible for the attack.
[src:hypersaline-lake/afar-region] Many governments around the world advise against traveling to the Afar region, citing increasing security concerns.
[src:hypersaline-lake/afar-region] Additionally, this region is also a hub for Afar–Somali clashes, due to many kebeles being put into the Afar region by the government.
[src:hypersaline-lake/afar-region] These include key towns like Gadamaytu, Undufo and Adaytu where battles between the Afar region and Somali region militaries happen.
[src:hypersaline-lake/afar-region] These conflicts have had many losses, and have led to the south-eastern parts of the region being an unstable zone.
[src:hypersaline-lake/afar-region] Hadar, a community in Afar, was the site of the discovery in 1973–1974 of "Lucy", the *Australopithecus afarensis* skeletal remains, by Donald Johanson of the Cleveland Museum of Natural History.
[src:hypersaline-lake/afar-region] On 5 March 2005, another skeleton, estimated to be 3.8 million years old and said to be the world's oldest bipedal hominid skeleton, was found in the region.
[src:hypersaline-lake/afar-region] Yohannes Haile-Selassie led digs there each year from 2004 to 2007.
[src:hypersaline-lake/afar-region] On 24 March 2006, it was reported that a "significantly complete" cranium had been found at Gawis in the Gona area.
[src:hypersaline-lake/afar-region] The cranium appears as an intermediate form between *Homo erectus* and *Homo sapiens*.
[src:hypersaline-lake/afar-region] On 1 October 2009, scientists reported that they had found a skeleton, which dates to around 4.4 million years ago.
[src:hypersaline-lake/afar-region] Named Ardi, it is a form of the species *Ardipithecus ramidus*.
[src:hypersaline-lake/afar-region] The specimen is a distant cousin of the *Australopithecus afarensis*, Lucy's species.
[src:hypersaline-lake/afar-region] In June 2010, the oldest direct evidence of stone tool manufacture was found in the Afar region and attributed to *Australopithecus afarensis*.
[src:hypersaline-lake/afar-region] In 2013, a graduate student from the Arizona State University discovered a hominid jawbone in the Ledi-Geraru region of Afar.
[src:hypersaline-lake/afar-region] Scientists estimated that the fossil dates to around 2.8 million years ago, which is 400,000 years before the next oldest hominid fossil remains.
[src:hypersaline-lake/afar-region] In 2015, a hominin jawbone and teeth was discovered in the Afar region.
[src:hypersaline-lake/afar-region] Scientists believe that the bones belonged to a previously undiscovered ancestor.
[src:hypersaline-lake/afar-region] The new species was named *Australopithecus deyiremeda*, meaning "close relative" in the native Afar language.
[src:hypersaline-lake/afar-region] The species lived around 3.5–3.3 million years ago, about the same time period as other hominins such as *Australopithecus afarensis*.
[src:hypersaline-lake/afar-region] Like other regions in Ethiopia, Afar Region is subdivided into administrative zones, in case of Afar, into six zones (and one special woreda, an administrative subdivision which is administering under Gabi Rasu (South Zone)/(Zone 3).
[src:hypersaline-lake/antarctica] Antarctica is, on average, the coldest, driest, and windiest of the continents, and has the highest average elevation.
[src:hypersaline-lake/antarctica] It is mainly a polar desert, with annual precipitation of over 200 mm (8 in) along the coast and far less inland.
[src:hypersaline-lake/antarctica] About 70% of the world's freshwater reserves are frozen in Antarctica, which, if melted, would raise global sea levels by almost 60 metres (200 ft).
[src:hypersaline-lake/antarctica] Antarctica holds the record for the lowest measured temperature on Earth, −89.2 °C (−128.6 °F).
[src:hypersaline-lake/antarctica] The coastal regions can reach temperatures over 10 °C (50 °F) in the summer.
[src:hypersaline-lake/antarctica] Native species of animals include mites, nematodes, penguins, seals and tardigrades.
[src:hypersaline-lake/antarctica] Where vegetation occurs, it is mostly in the form of lichen or moss.
[src:hypersaline-lake/antarctica] The ice shelves of Antarctica were probably first seen in 1820, during a Russian expedition led by Fabian Gottlieb von Bellingshausen and Mikhail Lazarev.
[src:hypersaline-lake/antarctica] The decades that followed saw further exploration by French, American, and British expeditions.
[src:hypersaline-lake/antarctica] The first confirmed landing was by a Norwegian team in 1895.
[src:hypersaline-lake/antarctica] In the early 20th century, there were a few expeditions into the interior of the continent.
[src:hypersaline-lake/antarctica] British explorers Douglas Mawson, Edgeworth David, and Alistair Mackay were the first to reach the magnetic South Pole in 1909, and the geographic South Pole was first reached in 1911 by Norwegian explorer Roald Amundsen.
[src:hypersaline-lake/antarctica] Antarctica is governed by about 30 countries, all of which are parties of the 1959 Antarctic Treaty System.
[src:hypersaline-lake/antarctica] According to the terms of the treaty, military activity, mining, nuclear explosions, and nuclear waste disposal are all prohibited in Antarctica.
[src:hypersaline-lake/antarctica] Tourism, fishing and research are the main human activities in and around Antarctica.
[src:hypersaline-lake/antarctica] During the summer months, about 5,000 people reside at research stations, a figure that drops to around 1,000 in the winter.
[src:hypersaline-lake/antarctica] Despite the continent's remoteness, human activity has a significant effect on it via pollution, ozone depletion, and climate change.
[src:hypersaline-lake/antarctica] The name given to the continent originates from the word *antarctic*, which comes from Middle French *antartique* or *antarctique* ('opposite to the Arctic') and, in turn, the Latin *antarcticus* ('opposite to the north').
[src:hypersaline-lake/antarctica] *Antarcticus* is derived from the Greek ἀντι- ('anti-') and ἀρκτικός (*arktikos*, 'of the Bear [Ursa Major], northern').
[src:hypersaline-lake/antarctica] The Greek philosopher Aristotle wrote in *Meteorology* about an "Antarctic region" in c.
[src:hypersaline-lake/antarctica] The Greek geographer Marinus of Tyre reportedly used the name in his world map from the second century AD, now lost.
[src:hypersaline-lake/antarctica] European ideas regarding the existence of a *Terra Australis*—a vast continent in the far south of the globe to balance the northern lands of Europe, Asia, and North Africa—had existed as an intellectual concept since classical antiquity.
[src:hypersaline-lake/antarctica] *Terra Australis* was therefore the name used to refer to all hypothetical landmasses proposed to be where Antarctica is now known to exist.
[src:hypersaline-lake/antarctica] Assertion of the presence of such a land lasted until the European discovery of Australia.
[src:hypersaline-lake/antarctica] During the early 19th century, explorer Matthew Flinders doubted the existence of a detached continent south of Australia (then called New Holland) and thus advocated for the "Terra Australis" name to be used for Australia instead.
[src:hypersaline-lake/antarctica] In 1824, the colonial authorities in Sydney officially renamed the continent of New Holland to Australia, leaving the term "Terra Australis" unavailable as a reference to Antarctica.
[src:hypersaline-lake/antarctica] Over the following decades, geographers used phrases such as "the Antarctic Continent".
[src:hypersaline-lake/antarctica] They searched for a more poetic replacement, suggesting names such as *Ultima* and *Antipodea*.
[src:hypersaline-lake/antarctica] *Antarctica* was adopted in the 1890s, with the first use of the name being attributed to the Scottish cartographer John George Bartholomew.
[src:hypersaline-lake/antarctica] Positioned asymmetrically around the South Pole and largely south of the Antarctic Circle (one of the five major circles of latitude that mark maps of the world), Antarctica is surrounded by the Southern Ocean.
[src:hypersaline-lake/antarctica] Rivers exist in Antarctica; the longest is the Onyx.
[src:hypersaline-lake/antarctica] Antarctica covers more than 14.2 million km2 (5,500,000 sq mi), almost double the area of Australia, making it the fifth-largest continent, and comparable to the surface area of Pluto.
[src:hypersaline-lake/antarctica] Its coastline is almost 18,000 km (11,200 mi) long: as of 1983, of the four coastal types, 44% of the coast is floating ice in the form of an ice shelf, 38% consists of ice walls that rest on rock, 13% is ice streams or the edge of glaciers, and the remaining 5% is exposed rock.
[src:hypersaline-lake/antarctica] The lakes that lie at the base of the continental ice sheet occur mainly in the McMurdo Dry Valleys or various oases.
[src:hypersaline-lake/antarctica] Lake Vostok, discovered beneath Russia's Vostok Station, is the largest subglacial lake globally and one of the largest lakes in the world.
[src:hypersaline-lake/antarctica] It was once believed that the lake had been sealed off for millions of years, but scientists now estimate its water is replaced by the slow melting and freezing of ice caps every 13,000 years.
[src:hypersaline-lake/antarctica] During the summer, the ice at the edges of the lakes can melt, and liquid moats temporarily form.
[src:hypersaline-lake/antarctica] Antarctica has both saline and freshwater lakes.
[src:hypersaline-lake/antarctica] Antarctica is divided into West Antarctica and East Antarctica by the Transantarctic Mountains, which stretch from Victoria Land to the Ross Sea.
[src:hypersaline-lake/antarctica] The vast majority of Antarctica is covered by the Antarctic ice sheet, which averages 1.9 km (1.2 mi) in thickness.
[src:hypersaline-lake/antarctica] The ice sheet extends to all but a few oases, which, with the exception of the McMurdo Dry Valleys, are located in coastal areas.
[src:hypersaline-lake/antarctica] Several Antarctic ice streams flow to one of the many Antarctic ice shelves, a process described by ice-sheet dynamics.
[src:hypersaline-lake/antarctica] East Antarctica comprises Coats Land, Queen Maud Land, Enderby Land, Mac.
[src:hypersaline-lake/antarctica] Robertson Land, Wilkes Land, and Victoria Land.
[src:hypersaline-lake/antarctica] All but a small portion of the region lies within the Eastern Hemisphere.
[src:hypersaline-lake/antarctica] East Antarctica is largely covered by the East Antarctic Ice Sheet.
[src:hypersaline-lake/antarctica] There are numerous islands surrounding Antarctica, most of which are volcanic and very young by geological standards.
[src:hypersaline-lake/antarctica] The most prominent exceptions to this are the islands of the Kerguelen Plateau, the earliest of which formed around 40 Ma.
[src:hypersaline-lake/antarctica] Vinson Massif, in the Ellsworth Mountains, is the highest peak in Antarctica at 4,892 m (16,050 ft).
[src:hypersaline-lake/antarctica] Mount Erebus on Ross Island is the world's southernmost active volcano and erupts around 10 times each day.
[src:hypersaline-lake/antarctica] Ash from eruptions has been found 300 kilometres (190 mi) from the volcanic crater.
[src:hypersaline-lake/antarctica] There is evidence of a large number of volcanoes under the ice, which could pose a risk to the ice sheet if activity levels were to rise.
[src:hypersaline-lake/antarctica] The ice dome known as Dome Argus in East Antarctica is the highest Antarctic ice feature, at 4,091 metres (13,422 ft).
[src:hypersaline-lake/antarctica] It is one of the world's coldest and driest places—temperatures there reach as low as −90 °C (−130 °F), and the annual precipitation is 1–3 cm (0.39–1.18 in).
[src:hypersaline-lake/antarctica] From the end of the Neoproterozoic era to the Cretaceous, Antarctica was part of the supercontinent Gondwana.
[src:hypersaline-lake/antarctica] Modern Antarctica was formed as Gondwana gradually broke apart beginning around 183 Ma.
[src:hypersaline-lake/antarctica] For a large proportion of the Phanerozoic, Antarctica had a tropical or temperate climate, and it was covered in forests.
[src:hypersaline-lake/antarctica] During the Cambrian period, Gondwana had a mild climate.
[src:hypersaline-lake/antarctica] West Antarctica was partially in the Northern Hemisphere, and during the time, large amounts of sandstones, limestones, and shales were deposited.
[src:hypersaline-lake/antarctica] East Antarctica was at the equator, where seafloor invertebrates and trilobites flourished in the tropical seas.
[src:hypersaline-lake/antarctica] By the start of the Devonian period (416 Ma), Gondwana was in more southern latitudes, and the climate was cooler, though fossils of land plants are known from then.
[src:hypersaline-lake/antarctica] Sand and silts were laid down in what is now the Ellsworth, Horlick, and Pensacola Mountains.
[src:hypersaline-lake/antarctica] Antarctica became glaciated during the Late Paleozoic icehouse beginning at the end of the Devonian period (360 Ma), though glaciation would substantially increase during the late Carboniferous.
[src:hypersaline-lake/antarctica] It drifted closer to the South Pole, and the climate cooled, though flora remained.
[src:hypersaline-lake/antarctica] After deglaciation during the latter half of the Early Permian, the land became dominated by glossopterids (an extinct group of seed plants with no close living relatives), most prominently *Glossopteris*, a tree interpreted as growing in waterlogged soils, which formed extensive coal deposits.
[src:hypersaline-lake/antarctica] Other plants found in Antarctica during the Permian include Cordaitales, sphenopsids, ferns, and lycophytes.
[src:hypersaline-lake/antarctica] At the end of the Permian, the climate became drier and hotter over much of Gondwana, and the glossopterid forest ecosystems collapsed as part of the Permian–Triassic extinction event.
[src:hypersaline-lake/antarctica] There is no evidence of any tetrapods having lived in Antarctica during the Paleozoic.
[src:hypersaline-lake/antarctica] The continued warming dried out much of Gondwana.
[src:hypersaline-lake/antarctica] During the Triassic period, Antarctica was dominated by seed ferns (pteridosperms) belonging to the genus *Dicroidium*, which grew as trees.
[src:hypersaline-lake/antarctica] Other associated Triassic flora included ginkgophytes, cycadophytes, conifers, and sphenopsids.
[src:hypersaline-lake/antarctica] Tetrapods first appeared in Antarctica during the Early Triassic epoch, with the earliest known fossils found in the Fremouw Formation of the Transantarctic Mountains.
[src:hypersaline-lake/antarctica] Synapsids (also known as "mammal-like reptiles") included species such as *Lystrosaurus*, and were common during the Early Triassic.
[src:hypersaline-lake/antarctica] The Antarctic Peninsula began to form during the Jurassic period (206 to 146 million years ago).
[src:hypersaline-lake/antarctica] Africa separated from Antarctica in the Jurassic around 160 Ma, followed by the Indian subcontinent in the early Cretaceous (about 125 Ma).
[src:hypersaline-lake/antarctica] *Ginkgo* trees, conifers, Bennettitales, horsetails, ferns and cycads were plentiful during the time.
[src:hypersaline-lake/antarctica] About 80 million years ago, flowering plants became the most diverse groups of plants on the continent.
[src:hypersaline-lake/antarctica] In West Antarctica, coniferous forests dominated throughout the Cretaceous period (146–66 Ma), though southern beech trees (*Nothofagus*) became prominent towards the end of the Cretaceous.
[src:hypersaline-lake/antarctica] During the early Paleogene, the Antarctic land bridge continued to connect Antarctica with South America as well as to southeastern Australia.
[src:hypersaline-lake/antarctica] Fauna from the La Meseta Formation in the Antarctic Peninsula, dating to the Eocene, is very similar to equivalent South American faunas; with marsupials, xenarthrans, litoptern, and astrapotherian ungulates, as well as gondwanatheres and possibly meridiolestidans.
[src:hypersaline-lake/antarctica] Marsupials are thought to have dispersed into Australia from South America via Antarctica by the early Eocene.
[src:hypersaline-lake/antarctica] Around 53 Ma, Australia-New Guinea separated from Antarctica, opening the Tasmanian Passage.
[src:hypersaline-lake/antarctica] The Drake Passage opened between Antarctica and South America around 30 Ma, resulting in the creation of the Antarctic Circumpolar Current that completely isolated the continent.
[src:hypersaline-lake/antarctica] Models of Antarctic geography suggest that this current, as well as a feedback loop caused by lowering CO2 levels, caused the creation of small yet permanent polar ice caps.
[src:hypersaline-lake/antarctica] As CO2 levels declined further the ice began to spread rapidly, replacing the forests that until then had covered Antarctica.
[src:hypersaline-lake/antarctica] Tundra ecosystems continued to exist on Antarctica until around 14–10 million years ago, when further cooling lead to their extermination.
[src:hypersaline-lake/antarctica] The geology of Antarctica, largely obscured by the continental ice sheet, can be studied via techniques such as remote sensing, ground-penetrating radar, and satellite imagery.
[src:hypersaline-lake/antarctica] Geologically, West Antarctica closely resembles the South American Andes.
[src:hypersaline-lake/antarctica] The Antarctic Peninsula was formed by geologic uplift and the transformation of sea bed sediments into metamorphic rocks.
[src:hypersaline-lake/antarctica] West Antarctica was formed by the merging of several continental plates, which created a number of mountain ranges in the region, the most prominent being the Ellsworth Mountains.
[src:hypersaline-lake/antarctica] The presence of the West Antarctic Rift System has resulted in volcanism along the border between West and East Antarctica, as well as the creation of the Transantarctic Mountains.
[src:hypersaline-lake/antarctica] Its formation began during the Archean Eon (4,000 Ma–2,500 Ma), and stopped during the Cambrian Period.
[src:hypersaline-lake/antarctica] It is built on a craton of rock, which is the basis of the Precambrian Shield.
[src:hypersaline-lake/antarctica] On top of the base are coal and sandstones, limestones, and shales that were laid down during the Devonian and Jurassic periods to form the Transantarctic Mountains.
[src:hypersaline-lake/antarctica] In coastal areas such as the Shackleton Range and Victoria Land, some faulting has occurred.
[src:hypersaline-lake/antarctica] Coal was first recorded in Antarctica near the Beardmore Glacier by Frank Wild on the *Nimrod* Expedition in 1907, and low-grade coal is known to exist across many parts of the Transantarctic Mountains.
[src:hypersaline-lake/antarctica] The Prince Charles Mountains contain deposits of iron ore.
[src:hypersaline-lake/antarctica] There are oil and natural gas fields in the Ross Sea.
[src:hypersaline-lake/antarctica] Antarctica is the coldest, windiest, and driest of Earth's continents.
[src:hypersaline-lake/antarctica] Near the coast, the temperature can exceed 10 °C in summer and fall to below −40 °C in winter.
[src:hypersaline-lake/antarctica] Over the elevated inland, it can rise to about −30 °C in summer but fall below −80 °C in winter.
[src:hypersaline-lake/antarctica] The lowest natural air temperature ever recorded on Earth was −89.2 °C (−128.6 °F) at the Russian Vostok Station in Antarctica on 21 July 1983.
[src:hypersaline-lake/antarctica] A lower air temperature of −94.7 °C (−138.5 °F) was recorded in 2010 by satellite—however, it may have been influenced by ground temperatures and was not recorded at a height of 2 m (7 ft) above the surface as required for official air temperature records.
[src:hypersaline-lake/antarctica] Antarctica is colder than the Arctic region, as much of Antarctica is over 3,000 m (9,800 ft) above sea level, where air temperatures are colder.
[src:hypersaline-lake/antarctica] The relative warmth of the Arctic Ocean is transferred through the Arctic sea ice and moderates temperatures in the Arctic region.
[src:hypersaline-lake/antarctica] Antarctica is a polar desert with little precipitation; the continent receives an average equivalent to about 150 mm (6 in) of water per year, mostly in the form of snow.
[src:hypersaline-lake/antarctica] The interior is drier and receives less than 50 mm (2 in) per year, whereas the coastal regions typically receive more than 200 mm (8 in).
[src:hypersaline-lake/antarctica] In a few blue-ice areas, the wind and sublimation remove more snow than is accumulated by precipitation.
[src:hypersaline-lake/antarctica] In the dry valleys, the same effect occurs over a rock base, leading to a barren and desiccated landscape.
[src:hypersaline-lake/antarctica] East Antarctica is colder than its western counterpart because of its higher elevation.
[src:hypersaline-lake/antarctica] Weather fronts rarely penetrate far into the continent, leaving the centre cold and dry, with moderate wind speeds.
[src:hypersaline-lake/antarctica] Heavy snowfalls are common on the coastal portion of Antarctica, where snowfalls of up to 1.22 m (48 in) in 48 hours have been recorded.
[src:hypersaline-lake/antarctica] At the continent's edge, strong katabatic winds off the polar plateau often blow at storm force.
[src:hypersaline-lake/antarctica] During the summer, more solar radiation reaches the surface at the South Pole than at the equator because of the 24 hours of sunlight received there each day.
[src:hypersaline-lake/antarctica] Antarctica's average ice mass change since 2002 has been on the order of 100 billion metric tons per year.
[src:hypersaline-lake/antarctica] The extent (area) of Antarctic sea ice reached a new low in 2023.
[src:hypersaline-lake/antarctica] Chart shows how little sea ice remains in the Antarctic summer, which at one point in February 2023 was only about 60% of its 1981–2010 average.
[src:hypersaline-lake/antarctica] Despite its isolation, Antarctica has experienced warming and ice loss in recent decades, driven by greenhouse gas emissions.
[src:hypersaline-lake/antarctica] West Antarctica warmed by over 0.1 °C per decade from the 1950s to the 2000s, and the exposed Antarctic Peninsula has warmed by 3 °C (5.4 °F) since the mid-20th century.
[src:hypersaline-lake/antarctica] The colder, stabler East Antarctica did not show any warming until the 2000s.
[src:hypersaline-lake/antarctica] Around Antarctica, the Southern Ocean has absorbed more oceanic heat than any other ocean, and has seen strong warming at depths below 2,000 m (6,600 ft).
[src:hypersaline-lake/antarctica] Around the West Antarctic, the ocean has warmed by 1 °C (1.8 °F) since 1955.
[src:hypersaline-lake/antarctica] The warming of the Southern Ocean around Antarctica has caused the weakening or collapse of ice shelves, which float just offshore of glaciers and stabilize them.
[src:hypersaline-lake/antarctica] Many coastal glaciers have been losing mass and retreating, causing net ice loss across Antarctica although the East Antarctic ice sheet continues to gain ice inland.
[src:hypersaline-lake/antarctica] By 2100, net ice loss from Antarctica is expected to add about 11 cm (5 in) to global sea level rise.
[src:hypersaline-lake/antarctica] Marine ice sheet instability may cause West Antarctica to contribute tens of centimeters more if it is triggered before 2100.
[src:hypersaline-lake/antarctica] With higher warming, instability would be much more likely and could double the 21st-century global sea level rise.
[src:hypersaline-lake/antarctica] The fresh meltwater from the ice dilutes the saline Antarctic bottom water weakening the lower cell of the Southern Ocean overturning circulation (SOOC).
[src:hypersaline-lake/antarctica] According to some research, a full collapse of the SOOC may occur at between 1.7 °C (3.1 °F) and 3 °C (5.4 °F) of global warming although the full effects are expected to occur over multiple centuries.
[src:hypersaline-lake/antarctica] They include less precipitation in the Southern Hemisphere but more in the Northern Hemisphere, an eventual decline of fisheries in the Southern Ocean and a potential collapse of certain marine ecosystems.
[src:hypersaline-lake/antarctica] While many Antarctic species remain undiscovered, there are documented increases in Antarctic flora, and large fauna such as penguins are already having difficulty retaining suitable habitat.
[src:hypersaline-lake/antarctica] On ice-free land, permafrost thaws release greenhouse gases and formerly frozen pollution.
[src:hypersaline-lake/antarctica] Antarctic warming and associated changes in Southern Ocean circulation can also influence climate patterns in parts of Africa, affecting regional rainfall and temperature variability.
[src:hypersaline-lake/antarctica] The West Antarctic ice sheet is likely to melt completely unless temperatures are reduced by 2 °C (3.6 °F) below 2020 levels.
[src:hypersaline-lake/antarctica] The loss of that ice sheet would take between 500 and 13,000 years.
[src:hypersaline-lake/antarctica] A sea level rise of 3.3 m (10 ft 10 in) would occur if the ice sheet collapses, which would leave ice caps on the mountains, and a rise of 4.3 m (14 ft 1 in) would occur if those ice caps also melt.
[src:hypersaline-lake/antarctica] The far more stable East Antarctic ice sheet may cause a sea level rise of only 0.5 m (1 ft 8 in) to 0.9 m (2 ft 11 in) from the current level of warming, a small fraction of the 53.3 m (175 ft) contained in the full ice sheet.
[src:hypersaline-lake/antarctica] With global warming being around 3 °C (5.4 °F), vulnerable areas like Wilkes Basin and Aurora Basin may collapse over around 2,000 years, potentially adding up to 6.4 m (21 ft 0 in) to sea levels.
[src:hypersaline-lake/antarctica] Scientists have studied the ozone layer in the atmosphere above Antarctica since the 1970s.
[src:hypersaline-lake/antarctica] In 1985, British scientists, working on data they had gathered at Halley Research Station on the Brunt Ice Shelf, discovered a large area of low ozone concentration over Antarctica.
[src:hypersaline-lake/antarctica] The 'ozone hole' covers almost the whole continent and was at its largest in September 2006; the longest-lasting event occurred in 2020.
[src:hypersaline-lake/antarctica] The depletion is caused by the emission of chlorofluorocarbons and halons into the atmosphere, which causes ozone to break down into other gases.
[src:hypersaline-lake/antarctica] The extreme cold conditions of Antarctica allow polar stratospheric clouds to form.
[src:hypersaline-lake/antarctica] The clouds act as catalysts for chemical reactions, which eventually lead to the destruction of ozone.
[src:hypersaline-lake/antarctica] The 1987 Montreal Protocol has restricted the emissions of ozone-depleting substances.
[src:hypersaline-lake/antarctica] The ozone hole above Antarctica is predicted to slowly disappear; by the 2060s, levels of ozone are expected to have returned to values last recorded in the 1980s.
[src:hypersaline-lake/antarctica] The ozone depletion can cause a cooling of around 6 °C (11 °F) in the stratosphere.
[src:hypersaline-lake/antarctica] The cooling strengthens the polar vortex and so prevents the outflow of the cold air near the South Pole, which in turn cools the continental mass of the East Antarctic ice sheet.
[src:hypersaline-lake/antarctica] The peripheral areas of Antarctica, especially the Antarctic Peninsula, are then subjected to higher temperatures, which accelerate the melting of the ice.
[src:hypersaline-lake/antarctica] Models suggest that ozone depletion and the enhanced polar vortex effect may also account for the period of increasing sea ice extent, lasting from when observation started in the late 1970s until 2014.
[src:hypersaline-lake/antarctica] Since then, the coverage of Antarctic sea ice has decreased rapidly.
[src:hypersaline-lake/antarctica] Most species in Antarctica seem to be the descendants of species that lived there millions of years ago.
[src:hypersaline-lake/antarctica] As such, they must have survived multiple glacial cycles.
[src:hypersaline-lake/antarctica] The species survived the periods of extremely cold climate in isolated warmer areas, such as those with geothermal heat or areas that remained ice-free throughout the colder climate.
[src:hypersaline-lake/antarctica] Invertebrate life of Antarctica includes species of microscopic mites such as *Alaskozetes antarcticus*, lice, fleas (*Glaciopsyllus antarcticus*), nematodes, tardigrades, rotifers, krill and springtails.
[src:hypersaline-lake/antarctica] The flightless midge *Belgica antarctica*, the largest purely terrestrial animal in Antarctica, reaches 6 mm (1⁄4 in) in size.
[src:hypersaline-lake/antarctica] Antarctic krill, which congregates in large schools, is the keystone species of the ecosystem of the Southern Ocean, being an important food organism for whales, seals, leopard seals, fur seals, squid, icefish, and many bird species, such as penguins and albatrosses.
[src:hypersaline-lake/antarctica] Some species of marine animals exist and rely, directly or indirectly, on phytoplankton.
[src:hypersaline-lake/antarctica] Antarctic sea life includes penguins, blue whales, orcas, colossal squids and fur seals.
[src:hypersaline-lake/antarctica] The Antarctic fur seal was very heavily hunted in the 18th and 19th centuries for its pelt by seal hunters from the United States and the United Kingdom.
[src:hypersaline-lake/antarctica] Leopard seals are apex predators in the Antarctic ecosystem and migrate across the Southern Ocean in search of food.
[src:hypersaline-lake/antarctica] There are approximately 40 bird species that breed on or close to Antarctica, including species of petrels, penguins, cormorants, and gulls.
[src:hypersaline-lake/antarctica] Various other bird species visit the ocean around Antarctica, including some that normally reside in the Arctic.
[src:hypersaline-lake/antarctica] The emperor penguin is the only penguin that breeds during the winter in Antarctica; it and the Adélie penguin breed farther south than any other penguin.
[src:hypersaline-lake/antarctica] A Census of Marine Life by some 500 researchers during the International Polar Year was released in 2010.
[src:hypersaline-lake/antarctica] The research found that more than 235 marine organisms live in both polar regions, having bridged the gap of 12,000 km (7,456 mi).
[src:hypersaline-lake/antarctica] Large animals such as some cetaceans and birds make the round trip annually.
[src:hypersaline-lake/antarctica] Smaller forms of life, such as sea cucumbers and free-swimming snails, are also found in both polar oceans.
[src:hypersaline-lake/antarctica] Factors that may aid in their distribution include temperature differences between the deep ocean at the poles and the equator of no more than 5 °C (9 °F) and the major current systems or marine conveyor belts which are able to transport eggs and larva.
[src:hypersaline-lake/antarctica] In January 2025, the detachment of the massive iceberg A-84 (comparable in size to the city of Chicago) from the George VI Ice Shelf provided a rare opportunity to explore the seafloor beneath floating ice shelves using robotic submersibles.
[src:hypersaline-lake/antarctica] Researchers uncovered ecosystems unexpectedly rich in large corals, ancient sponges, icefish, giant sea spiders, and even octopuses at depths of up to 1,300 metres (4,300 ft).
[src:hypersaline-lake/antarctica] These ecosystems may harbor novel species that have remained concealed for centuries, sustained by nutrient-bearing ocean currents.
[src:hypersaline-lake/antarctica] About 1,150 species of fungi have been recorded in the Antarctic region, of which about 750 are non-lichen-forming.
[src:hypersaline-lake/antarctica] Some of the species, having evolved under extreme conditions, have colonised structural cavities within porous rocks and have contributed to shaping the rock formations of the McMurdo Dry Valleys and surrounding mountain ridges.
[src:hypersaline-lake/antarctica] The simplified morphology of such fungi, along with their similar biological structures, metabolism systems capable of remaining active at very low temperatures, and reduced life cycles, make them well suited to such environments.
[src:hypersaline-lake/antarctica] Their thick-walled and strongly melanised cells make them resistant to UV radiation.
[src:hypersaline-lake/antarctica] An Antarctic endemic species, the crust-like lichen *Buellia frigida*, has been used as a model organism in astrobiology research.
[src:hypersaline-lake/antarctica] The same features can be observed in algae and cyanobacteria, suggesting that they are adaptations to the conditions prevailing in Antarctica.
[src:hypersaline-lake/antarctica] This has led to speculation that life on Mars might have been similar to Antarctic fungi, such as *Cryomyces antarcticus* and *Cryomyces minteri*.
[src:hypersaline-lake/antarctica] Some of the species of fungi, which are apparently endemic to Antarctica, live in bird dung, and have evolved so they can grow inside extremely cold dung, but can also pass through the intestines of warm-blooded animals.
[src:hypersaline-lake/antarctica] Throughout its history, Antarctica has seen a wide variety of plant life.
[src:hypersaline-lake/antarctica] In the Cretaceous, it was dominated by a fern-conifer ecosystem, which changed into a temperate rainforest by the end of that period.
[src:hypersaline-lake/antarctica] During the colder Neogene (17–2.5 Ma), a tundra ecosystem replaced the rainforests.
[src:hypersaline-lake/antarctica] The climate of present-day Antarctica does not allow extensive vegetation to form.
[src:hypersaline-lake/antarctica] A combination of freezing temperatures, poor soil quality, and a lack of moisture and sunlight inhibit plant growth, causing low species diversity and limited distribution.
[src:hypersaline-lake/antarctica] The flora largely consists of bryophytes (25 species of liverworts and 100 species of mosses).
[src:hypersaline-lake/antarctica] There are three species of flowering plants, all of which are found in the Antarctic Peninsula: *Deschampsia antarctica* (Antarctic hair grass), *Colobanthus quitensis* (Antarctic pearlwort) and the non-native *Poa annua* (annual bluegrass).
[src:hypersaline-lake/antarctica] Of the 700 species of algae in Antarctica, around half are marine phytoplankton.
[src:hypersaline-lake/antarctica] Multicoloured snow algae are especially abundant in the coastal regions during the summer.
[src:hypersaline-lake/antarctica] Even sea ice can harbour unique ecological communities, as it expels all salt from the water when it freezes, which accumulates into pockets of brine that also harbour dormant microorganisms.
[src:hypersaline-lake/antarctica] When the ice begins to melt, brine pockets expand and can combine to form brine channels, and the algae inside the pockets can reawaken and thrive until the next freeze.
[src:hypersaline-lake/antarctica] Bacteria have also been found as deep as 800 m (0.50 mi) under the ice.
[src:hypersaline-lake/antarctica] It is thought to be likely that there exists a native bacterial community within the subterranean water body of Lake Vostok.
[src:hypersaline-lake/antarctica] The existence of life there is thought to strengthen the argument for the possibility of life on Jupiter's moon Europa, which may have water beneath its water-ice crust.
[src:hypersaline-lake/antarctica] There exists a community of extremophile bacteria in the highly alkaline waters of Lake Untersee.
[src:hypersaline-lake/antarctica] The prevalence of highly resilient creatures in such inhospitable areas could further bolster the argument for extraterrestrial life in cold, methane-rich environments.
[src:hypersaline-lake/antarctica] The first international agreement to protect Antarctica's biodiversity was adopted in 1964.
[src:hypersaline-lake/antarctica] The overfishing of krill (an animal that plays a large role in the Antarctic ecosystem) led officials to enact regulations on fishing.
[src:hypersaline-lake/antarctica] The Convention for the Conservation of Antarctic Marine Living Resources, an international treaty that came into force in 1980, regulates fisheries, aiming to preserve ecological relationships.
[src:hypersaline-lake/antarctica] Despite these regulations, illegal fishing—particularly of the highly prized Patagonian toothfish which is marketed as Chilean sea bass in the U.S.—remains a problem.
[src:hypersaline-lake/antarctica] In analogy to the 1980 treaty on sustainable fishing, countries led by New Zealand and the United States negotiated a treaty on mining.
[src:hypersaline-lake/antarctica] This Convention on the Regulation of Antarctic Mineral Resource Activities was adopted in 1988.
[src:hypersaline-lake/antarctica] After a strong campaign from environmental organisations, first Australia and then France decided not to ratify the treaty.
[src:hypersaline-lake/antarctica] Instead, countries adopted the Protocol on Environmental Protection to the Antarctic Treaty (the Madrid Protocol), which entered into force in 1998.
[src:hypersaline-lake/antarctica] The Madrid Protocol bans all mining, designating the continent as a "natural reserve devoted to peace and science".
[src:hypersaline-lake/antarctica] The pressure group Greenpeace established a base on Ross Island from 1987 to 1992 as part of its attempt to establish the continent as a World Park.
[src:hypersaline-lake/antarctica] The Southern Ocean Whale Sanctuary was established in 1994 by the International Whaling Commission.
[src:hypersaline-lake/antarctica] It covers 50 million km2 (19 million sq mi) and completely surrounds the Antarctic continent.
[src:hypersaline-lake/antarctica] All commercial whaling is banned in the zone, though Japan has continued to hunt whales in the area, ostensibly for research purposes.
[src:hypersaline-lake/antarctica] Despite these protections, the biodiversity in Antarctica is still at risk from human activities.
[src:hypersaline-lake/antarctica] Specially protected areas cover less than 2% of the area and provide better protection for animals with popular appeal than for less visible animals.
[src:hypersaline-lake/antarctica] There are more terrestrial protected areas than marine protected areas.
[src:hypersaline-lake/antarctica] Ecosystems are impacted by local and global threats, notably pollution, the invasion of non-native species, and the various effects of climate change.
[src:hypersaline-lake/antarctica] Early world maps, like the 1513 Piri Reis map, feature the hypothetical continent *Terra Australis*.
[src:hypersaline-lake/antarctica] Much larger than and unrelated to Antarctica, *Terra Australis* was a landmass that classical scholars presumed necessary to balance the known lands in the northern hemisphere.
[src:hypersaline-lake/antarctica] Captain James Cook's ships, HMS *Resolution* and *Adventure*, crossed the Antarctic Circle on 17 January 1773, in December 1773, and again in January 1774.
[src:hypersaline-lake/antarctica] Cook came within about 120 km (75 mi) of the Antarctic coast before retreating in the face of field ice in January 1773.
[src:hypersaline-lake/antarctica] In 1775, he called the existence of a polar continent "probable", and in another copy of his journal he wrote: "[I] firmly believe it and it's more than probable that we have seen a part of it".
[src:hypersaline-lake/antarctica] Sealers were among the earliest to go closer to the Antarctic landmass, perhaps in the earlier part of the 19th century.
[src:hypersaline-lake/antarctica] The oldest known human remains in the Antarctic region was a skull, dated from 1819 to 1825, that belonged to a young woman on Yamana Beach at the South Shetland Islands.
[src:hypersaline-lake/antarctica] The woman, who was likely to have been part of a sealing expedition, was found in 1985.
[src:hypersaline-lake/antarctica] The first person to see Antarctica or its ice shelf was long thought to have been the British sailor Edward Bransfield, a captain in the Royal Navy, who discovered the tip of the Antarctic peninsula on 30 January 1820.
[src:hypersaline-lake/antarctica] However, a captain in the Imperial Russian Navy, Fabian Gottlieb von Bellingshausen, recorded seeing an ice shelf on 27 January.
[src:hypersaline-lake/antarctica] The American sealer Nathaniel Palmer, whose sealing ship was in the region at this time, may also have been the first to sight the Antarctic Peninsula.
[src:hypersaline-lake/antarctica] The sighting happened three days before Bransfield sighted the land of the Trinity Peninsula of Antarctica, as opposed to the ice of an ice shelf, and 10 months before Palmer did so in November 1820.
[src:hypersaline-lake/antarctica] The first documented landing on Antarctica was by the English-born American sealer John Davis, apparently at Hughes Bay on 7 February 1821, although some historians dispute this claim, as there is no evidence Davis landed on the Antarctic continent rather than an offshore island.
[src:hypersaline-lake/antarctica] The American captain Charles Wilkes led an expedition in 1838–1839 and was the first to claim he had discovered the continent.
[src:hypersaline-lake/antarctica] The British naval officer James Clark Ross failed to realise that what he referred to as "the various patches of land recently discovered by the American, French and English navigators on the verge of the Antarctic Circle" were connected to form a single continent.
[src:hypersaline-lake/antarctica] The American explorer Mercator Cooper landed on East Antarctica on 26 January 1853.
[src:hypersaline-lake/antarctica] The first confirmed landing on the continental mass of Antarctica occurred in 1895 when the Norwegian-Swedish whaling ship *Antarctic* reached Cape Adare.
[src:hypersaline-lake/antarctica] During the *Nimrod* Expedition led by the British explorer Ernest Shackleton in 1907, parties led by Edgeworth David became the first to climb Mount Erebus and to reach the south magnetic pole.
[src:hypersaline-lake/antarctica] Douglas Mawson, who assumed the leadership of the Magnetic Pole party on their perilous return, retired in 1931.
[src:hypersaline-lake/antarctica] Between December 1908 and February 1909, Shackleton and three members of his expedition became the first humans to traverse the Ross Ice Shelf, the first to cross the Transantarctic Mountains (via the Beardmore Glacier), and the first to set foot on the south Polar Plateau.
[src:hypersaline-lake/antarctica] On 14 December 1911, an expedition led by Norwegian explorer Roald Amundsen from the ship *Fram* became the first to reach the geographic South Pole, using a route from the Bay of Whales and up the Axel Heiberg Glacier.
[src:hypersaline-lake/antarctica] One month later, the doomed *Terra Nova* Expedition reached the pole.
[src:hypersaline-lake/antarctica] Byrd led four expeditions to Antarctica during the 1920s, 1930s, and 1940s, using the first mechanised tractors.
[src:hypersaline-lake/antarctica] His expeditions conducted extensive geographical and scientific research, and he is credited with surveying a larger region of the continent than any other explorer.
[src:hypersaline-lake/antarctica] In 1937, Ingrid Christensen became the first woman to step onto the Antarctic mainland.
[src:hypersaline-lake/antarctica] Caroline Mikkelsen had landed on an island of Antarctica, earlier in 1935.
[src:hypersaline-lake/antarctica] The South Pole was next reached on 31 October 1956, when a U.S.
[src:hypersaline-lake/antarctica] Navy group led by Rear Admiral George J.
[src:hypersaline-lake/antarctica] Six women were flown to the South Pole as a publicity stunt in 1969.
[src:hypersaline-lake/antarctica] In the summer of 1996–1997, Norwegian explorer Børge Ousland became the first person to cross Antarctica alone from coast to coast, helped by a kite on parts of the journey.
[src:hypersaline-lake/antarctica] Ousland holds the record for the fastest unsupported journey to the South Pole, taking 34 days.
[src:hypersaline-lake/antarctica] The first semi-permanent inhabitants of regions near Antarctica (areas situated south of the Antarctic Convergence) were British and American sealers who used to spend a year or more on South Georgia, from 1786 onward.
[src:hypersaline-lake/antarctica] During the whaling era, which lasted until 1966, the population of the island varied from over 1,000 in the summer (over 2,000 in some years) to some 200 in the winter.
[src:hypersaline-lake/antarctica] Most of the whalers were Norwegian, with an increasing proportion from Britain.
[src:hypersaline-lake/antarctica] The first child born in the southern polar region was a Norwegian girl, Solveig Gunbjørg Jacobsen, born in Grytviken on 8 October 1913.
[src:hypersaline-lake/antarctica] Emilio Marcos Palma was the first person born on the Antarctic mainland at the Esperanza Base of the Argentine Army, on 7 January 1978.
[src:hypersaline-lake/antarctica] Antarctica's population consists mostly of the staff of research stations in Antarctica (which are continuously maintained despite the population decline in the winter), although there are 2 all-civilian bases in Antarctica: the Esperanza Base and the Villa Las Estrellas base.
[src:hypersaline-lake/antarctica] The number of people conducting and supporting scientific research and other work on the continent and its nearby islands varies from about 1,200 in winter to about 4,800 in the summer, with an additional 136 people in the winter to 266 people in the summer from the 2 civilian bases (as of 2017).
[src:hypersaline-lake/antarctica] Some of the research stations are staffed year-round, the winter-over personnel typically arriving from their home countries for a one-year assignment.
[src:hypersaline-lake/antarctica] Christianity is the most common Antarctic religion, with 8 chapels of various Christian denominations located there; due to the difficulties involved with transporting religious officials to the continent most services are performed online.
[src:hypersaline-lake/antarctica] Antarctic English, a distinct variety of the English language, has been found to be spoken by people living on Antarctica and the subantarctic islands.
[src:hypersaline-lake/antarctica] Antarctica's status is regulated by the 1959 Antarctic Treaty and other related agreements, collectively called the Antarctic Treaty System.
[src:hypersaline-lake/antarctica] Antarctica is defined as all land and ice shelves south of 60° S for the purposes of the Treaty System.
[src:hypersaline-lake/antarctica] The treaty was signed by twelve countries, including the Soviet Union, the United Kingdom, Argentina, Chile, Australia, and the United States.
[src:hypersaline-lake/antarctica] Since 1959, a further 42 countries have acceded to the treaty.
[src:hypersaline-lake/antarctica] Countries can participate in decision-making if they can demonstrate that they do significant research on Antarctica; as of 2022, 29 countries have this 'consultative status'.
[src:hypersaline-lake/antarctica] Decisions are based on consensus, instead of a vote.
[src:hypersaline-lake/antarctica] The treaty set aside Antarctica as a scientific preserve and established freedom of scientific investigation and environmental protection.
[src:hypersaline-lake/antarctica] Several countries with research stations in Antarctica allow their citizens stationed in the continent to vote in their elections.
[src:hypersaline-lake/antarctica] In 1539, the King of Spain, Charles V, created the Governorate of Terra Australis, which encompassed lands south of the Strait of Magellan and thus the then-hypothetical Antarctica, granting this Governorate to Pedro Sancho de la Hoz.
[src:hypersaline-lake/antarctica] Spain claimed all the territories to the south of the Strait of Magellan until the South Pole, with eastern and western borders to these claims specified in the Treaty of Tordesillas and Zaragoza respectively.
[src:hypersaline-lake/antarctica] In 1555 the claim was incorporated to Chile.
[src:hypersaline-lake/antarctica] In the present, sovereignty over regions of Antarctica is claimed by seven different countries.
[src:hypersaline-lake/antarctica] While a few of these countries have mutually recognised each other's claims, the validity of the claims is not recognised universally.
[src:hypersaline-lake/antarctica] New claims on Antarctica have been suspended since 1959, although in 2015, Norway formally defined Queen Maud Land as including the unclaimed area between it and the South Pole.
[src:hypersaline-lake/antarctica] The Argentine, British, and Chilean claims overlap and have caused friction.
[src:hypersaline-lake/antarctica] In 2012, after the British Foreign & Commonwealth Office designated a previously unnamed area Queen Elizabeth Land in tribute to Queen Elizabeth II's Diamond Jubilee, the Argentine government protested against the claim.
[src:hypersaline-lake/antarctica] The UK passed some of the areas it claimed to Australia and New Zealand after they achieved independence.
[src:hypersaline-lake/antarctica] The claims by Britain, Australia, New Zealand, France, and Norway do not overlap and are recognised by each other.
[src:hypersaline-lake/antarctica] Other member nations of the Antarctic Treaty do not recognise any claim, yet have shown some form of territorial interest in the past.
[src:hypersaline-lake/antarctica] Deposits of coal, hydrocarbons, iron ore, platinum, copper, chromium, nickel, gold, and other minerals have been found in Antarctica, but not in large enough quantities to extract.
[src:hypersaline-lake/antarctica] The Protocol on Environmental Protection to the Antarctic Treaty, which came into effect in 1998 and is due to be reviewed in 2048, restricts the exploitation of Antarctic resources, including minerals.
[src:hypersaline-lake/antarctica] Tourists have been visiting Antarctica since 1957.
[src:hypersaline-lake/antarctica] Tourism is subject to the provisions of the Antarctic Treaty and Environmental Protocol; the self-regulatory body for the industry is the International Association of Antarctica Tour Operators.
[src:hypersaline-lake/antarctica] Tourists arrive by small or medium ship at specific scenic locations with accessible concentrations of iconic wildlife.
[src:hypersaline-lake/antarctica] Much Antarctic tourism is based around bird watching tours due to the high numbers of penguins on the continent.
[src:hypersaline-lake/antarctica] McDonald Beach is known to be a high-traffic area for tourists watching the Adélie penguin population there.
[src:hypersaline-lake/antarctica] Overland sightseeing flights operated out of Australia and New Zealand until the Mount Erebus disaster in 1979, when an Air New Zealand plane crashed into Mount Erebus, killing all of the 257 people on board.
[src:hypersaline-lake/antarctica] Qantas resumed commercial overflights to Antarctica from Australia in the mid-1990s.
[src:hypersaline-lake/antarctica] Over 74,000 tourists visited the region during the 2019–2020 season, of which 18,500 travelled on cruise ships but did not leave them to explore on land.
[src:hypersaline-lake/antarctica] Some nature conservation groups have expressed concern over the potential adverse effects caused by the influx of visitors and have called for limits on the size of visiting cruise ships and a tourism quota.
[src:hypersaline-lake/antarctica] The primary response by Antarctic Treaty parties has been to develop guidelines that set landing limits and closed or restricted zones on the more frequently visited sites.
[src:hypersaline-lake/antarctica] In 2017, there were more than 4,400 scientists undertaking research in Antarctica, a number that fell to just over 1,100 in the winter.
[src:hypersaline-lake/antarctica] There are over 70 permanent and seasonal research stations on the continent; the largest, United States' McMurdo Station, is capable of housing more than 1,000 people.
[src:hypersaline-lake/antarctica] The British Antarctic Survey has five major research stations on Antarctica, one of which is completely portable.
[src:hypersaline-lake/antarctica] The Belgian Princess Elisabeth station is one of the most modern stations and the first to be carbon-neutral.
[src:hypersaline-lake/antarctica] Argentina, Australia, Chile, and Russia also have a large scientific presence on Antarctica.
[src:hypersaline-lake/antarctica] Many nations release strategy reports designed to guide their research efforts on Antarctica.
[src:hypersaline-lake/antarctica] The British Antarctic Survey (BAS), Australian Antarctic Program (AAP) and United States Antarctic Program (USAP) have all released such reports, largely focusing on how changes in Antarctica's climate may impact their respective home countries and the global climate.
[src:hypersaline-lake/antarctica] Geologists primarily study plate tectonics, meteorites, and the breakup of Gondwana.
[src:hypersaline-lake/antarctica] Glaciologists study the history and dynamics of floating ice, seasonal snow, glaciers, and ice sheets.
[src:hypersaline-lake/antarctica] Biologists, in addition to researching wildlife, are interested in how low temperatures and the presence of humans affect adaptation and survival strategies in organisms.
[src:hypersaline-lake/antarctica] Biomedical scientists have made discoveries concerning the spreading of viruses and the body's response to extreme seasonal temperatures.
[src:hypersaline-lake/antarctica] The view of space from Earth is improved by a thinner atmosphere at higher elevations and a lack of water vapour in the atmosphere caused by freezing temperatures.
[src:hypersaline-lake/antarctica] Astrophysicists at the Amundsen–Scott South Pole Station study cosmic microwave background radiation and neutrinos from space.
[src:hypersaline-lake/antarctica] The largest neutrino detector in the world, the IceCube Neutrino Observatory, is at the Amundsen-Scott Station.
[src:hypersaline-lake/antarctica] It consists of around 5,500 digital optical modules, some of which reach a depth of 2,450 m (8,040 ft), that are held in 1 km3 (0.24 cu mi) of ice.
[src:hypersaline-lake/antarctica] Scientists also observed higher radiation dose rates around the coast of Antarctica compared with the global average: this is attributed to cosmic rays going through the thinner atmosphere compared to equatorial latitudes.
[src:hypersaline-lake/antarctica] Antarctica provides a unique environment for the study of meteorites: the dry polar desert preserves them well, and meteorites older than a million years have been found.
[src:hypersaline-lake/antarctica] They are relatively easy to find, as the dark stone meteorites stand out in a landscape of ice and snow, and the flow of ice accumulates them in certain areas.
[src:hypersaline-lake/antarctica] The Adelie Land meteorite, discovered in 1912, was the first to be found.
[src:hypersaline-lake/antarctica] Meteorites contain clues about the composition of the Solar System and its early development.
[src:hypersaline-lake/antarctica] Most meteorites come from asteroids, but a few meteorites found in Antarctica came from the Moon and Mars.
[src:hypersaline-lake/antarctica] The first motion-picture footage of Antarctica is thought to have been hand-cranked by a unknown member of the Scottish National Antarctic Expedition in early 1904.
[src:hypersaline-lake/antarctica] Among the fiction films shot partly or entirely in Antarctica are *Mr.
[src:hypersaline-lake/antarctica] Forbush and the Penguins*, a 1971 British comedy starring John Hurt; *Antarctica*, a 1983 Japanese survival drama with music by Vangelis; and *South of Sanity*, a 2012 low-budget British horror.
[src:hypersaline-lake/antarctica] The Winter International Film Festival of Antarctica (WIFFA), established in 2006 as a way to combat social isolation, is held annually for those wintering on the continent.
[src:hypersaline-lake/antarctica] WIFFA is open to short films of 5 minutes or less, shot during a 48-hour window.
[src:hypersaline-lake/antarctica] The southernmost music festival in the world, Icestock, has been held at McMurdo Station since 1989.
[src:hypersaline-lake/antarctica] The organizers, performers, and attendees of Icestock are all personnel working at McMurdo or nearby Scott Base.
[src:hypersaline-lake/antarctica] Sporting events held on Antarctica include the Antarctic Ice Marathon & 100k ultra race, Antarctica Marathon and Antarctica Cup Yacht Race.
[src:hypersaline-lake/antarctica] Association football has been played since the early twentieth century, with teams representing bases or visiting ships.
[src:hypersaline-lake/antarctica] There are two principal holidays celebrated across Antarctica: Midwinter Day on the day of the southern winter solstice (June 20 or 21) and Antarctica Day on December 1, which commemorates the signing of the Antarctic Treaty in 1959.
[src:hypersaline-lake/arctic] The **Arctic** (/ˈɑːr(k)tɪk/; from Ancient Greek ἄρκτος*(*árktos*)* 'bear') is the polar region of Earth that surrounds the North Pole, lying north of the Arctic Circle.
[src:hypersaline-lake/arctic] Land within the Arctic region has seasonally varying snow and ice cover, with predominantly treeless permafrost under the tundra.
[src:hypersaline-lake/arctic] Arctic seas contain seasonal sea ice in many places.
[src:hypersaline-lake/arctic] The Arctic region is a unique area among Earth's ecosystems.
[src:hypersaline-lake/arctic] The cultures in the region and the Arctic indigenous peoples have adapted to its cold and extreme conditions.
[src:hypersaline-lake/arctic] Life in the Arctic includes zooplankton and phytoplankton, fish and marine mammals, birds, land animals, plants, and human societies.
[src:hypersaline-lake/arctic] Arctic land is bordered by the subarctic.
[src:hypersaline-lake/arctic] There are several definitions of what area is contained within the Arctic.
[src:hypersaline-lake/arctic] The area can be defined as north of the Arctic Circle (about 66° 34'N), the approximate southern limit of the midnight sun and the polar night.
[src:hypersaline-lake/arctic] Another definition of the Arctic, which is popular with ecologists, is the region in the Northern Hemisphere where the average temperature for the warmest month (July) is below 10 °C (50 °F); the northernmost tree line roughly follows the isotherm at the boundary of this region.
[src:hypersaline-lake/arctic] The climate of the Arctic region is characterized by cold winters and cool summers.
[src:hypersaline-lake/arctic] Its precipitation mostly comes in the form of snow and is low, with most of the area receiving less than 50 cm (20 in).
[src:hypersaline-lake/arctic] High winds often stir up snow, creating the illusion of continuous snowfall.
[src:hypersaline-lake/arctic] Average winter temperatures can go as low as −40 °C (−40 °F), and the coldest recorded temperature is approximately −68 °C (−90 °F).
[src:hypersaline-lake/arctic] Coastal Arctic climates are moderated by oceanic influences, having generally warmer temperatures and heavier snowfalls than the colder and drier interior areas.
[src:hypersaline-lake/arctic] The Arctic is affected by current global warming, leading to climate change in the Arctic, including Arctic sea ice decline, diminished ice in the Greenland ice sheet, and Arctic methane emissions as the permafrost thaws.
[src:hypersaline-lake/arctic] The melting of Greenland's ice sheet is linked to polar amplification.
[src:hypersaline-lake/arctic] Due to the poleward migration of the planet's isotherms (about 56 km (35 mi) per decade during the past 30 years as a consequence of global warming), the Arctic region (as defined by tree line and temperature) is currently shrinking.
[src:hypersaline-lake/arctic] Perhaps the most alarming result of this is Arctic sea ice shrinkage.
[src:hypersaline-lake/arctic] There is a large variance in predictions of Arctic sea ice loss, with models showing near-complete to complete loss in September from 2035 to sometime around 2067.
[src:hypersaline-lake/arctic] Arctic life is characterized by adaptation to short growing seasons with long periods of sunlight, and cold, dark, snow-covered winter conditions, with soil depth constrained by permafrost.
[src:hypersaline-lake/arctic] In the Arctic Circle, up to 24 hours of daylight is experienced at the summer solstice in June and up to 24 hours of darkness during the winter solstice in December which has an important impact on the ecology of the region.
[src:hypersaline-lake/arctic] Arctic vegetation is composed of plants such as dwarf shrubs, graminoids, herbs, lichens, and mosses, which all grow relatively close to the ground, forming tundra.
[src:hypersaline-lake/arctic] An example of a dwarf shrub is the bearberry.
[src:hypersaline-lake/arctic] As one moves northward, the amount of warmth available for plant growth decreases considerably.
[src:hypersaline-lake/arctic] In the northernmost areas, plants are at their metabolic limits, and small differences in the total amount of summer warmth make large differences in the amount of energy available for maintenance, growth, and reproduction.
[src:hypersaline-lake/arctic] Colder summer temperatures cause the size, abundance, productivity, and variety of plants to decrease.
[src:hypersaline-lake/arctic] Trees cannot grow in the Arctic, but in its warmest parts, shrubs are common and can reach 2 m (6 ft 7 in) in height; sedges, mosses and lichens can form thick layers.
[src:hypersaline-lake/arctic] In the coldest parts of the Arctic, much of the ground is bare; non-vascular plants such as lichens and mosses predominate, along with a few scattered grasses and forbs (like the Arctic poppy).
[src:hypersaline-lake/arctic] Herbivores on the tundra include the Arctic hare, lemming, muskox, and reindeer (caribou).
[src:hypersaline-lake/arctic] They are preyed on by the snowy owl, Arctic fox, grizzly bear, and Arctic wolf.
[src:hypersaline-lake/arctic] The polar bear is also a predator, though it prefers to hunt for marine life from the ice.
[src:hypersaline-lake/arctic] There are also many birds (some 200 species breed in the Arctic) and marine species endemic to the colder regions.
[src:hypersaline-lake/arctic] Other terrestrial animals include wolverines, moose, Dall sheep, ermines, and Arctic ground squirrels.
[src:hypersaline-lake/arctic] Marine mammals include seals, walruses, and several species of cetacean—baleen whales and also narwhals, orcas, and belugas.
[src:hypersaline-lake/arctic] There are copious natural resources in the Arctic (oil, gas, minerals, freshwater, fish, and, if the subarctic is included, forest) to which modern technology and the economic opening up of Russia have given significant new opportunities.
[src:hypersaline-lake/arctic] The interest in the tourism industry is also on the increase.
[src:hypersaline-lake/arctic] The Arctic contains some of the last and most extensive continuous wilderness areas in the world, and its significance in preserving biodiversity and genotypes is considerable.
[src:hypersaline-lake/arctic] The increasing presence of humans fragments vital habitats.
[src:hypersaline-lake/arctic] The Arctic is particularly susceptible to the abrasion of groundcover and to the disturbance of the rare breeding grounds of the animals that are characteristic of the region.
[src:hypersaline-lake/arctic] The Arctic also holds 1/5 of the Earth's water supply.
[src:hypersaline-lake/arctic] During the Cretaceous period, the Arctic still had seasonal snows, though only a light dusting and not enough to permanently hinder plant growth.
[src:hypersaline-lake/arctic] Animals such as the *Chasmosaurus*, *Hypacrosaurus*, *Troodon*, and *Edmontosaurus* may have all migrated north to take advantage of the summer growing season, and migrated south to warmer climes when winter came.
[src:hypersaline-lake/arctic] A similar situation may also have been found amongst dinosaurs that lived in Antarctic regions, such as the *Muttaburrasaurus* of Australia.
[src:hypersaline-lake/arctic] However, others claim that dinosaurs lived year-round at very high latitudes, such as near the Colville River, which is now at about 70° N but at the time (70 million years ago) was 10° further north.
[src:hypersaline-lake/arctic] The earliest inhabitants of North America's central and eastern Arctic are referred to as the Arctic small tool tradition (AST) and existed c.
[src:hypersaline-lake/arctic] AST consisted of several Paleo-Eskimo cultures, including the Independence cultures and Pre-Dorset cultures.
[src:hypersaline-lake/arctic] The Dorset culture (Inuktitut: *Tuniit* or *Tunit*) refers to the next inhabitants of central and eastern Arctic.
[src:hypersaline-lake/arctic] The Dorset culture emerged across the North American Arctic through a gradual process of cultural and technological adaptation to changing environmental conditions and resource availability between 1050 and 500 BCE.
[src:hypersaline-lake/arctic] With the exception of the Quebec / Labrador peninsula, the Dorset culture vanished around 1500 CE.
[src:hypersaline-lake/arctic] Supported by genetic testing, evidence shows that descendants of the Dorset culture, known as the Sadlermiut, survived in Aivilik, Southampton and Coats Islands, until the beginning of the 20th century.
[src:hypersaline-lake/arctic] The Dorset / Thule culture transition dates around the ninth–10th centuries CE.
[src:hypersaline-lake/arctic] Scientists theorize that there may have been cross-contact between the two cultures with the sharing of technology, such as fashioning harpoon heads, or the Thule may have found Dorset remnants and adapted their ways with the predecessor culture.
[src:hypersaline-lake/arctic] The evidence suggested that Inuit descend from the Birnirk of Siberia, through the Thule culture expanded into northern Canada and Greenland, where they genetically and culturally completely replaced the Indigenous Dorset people sometime after 1300 CE.
[src:hypersaline-lake/arctic] By 1300 CE, the Inuit, present-day Arctic inhabitants and descendants of Thule culture, had settled in west Greenland and moved into east Greenland over the following century (Inughuit, Kalaallit and Tunumiit are modern Greenlandic Inuit groups descended from Thule).
[src:hypersaline-lake/arctic] Over time, the Inuit have migrated throughout the Arctic regions of Eastern Russia, the United States, Canada, and Greenland.
[src:hypersaline-lake/arctic] Other Circumpolar North indigenous peoples include the Chukchi, Evenks, Iñupiat, Khanty, Koryaks, Nenets, Sámi, Yukaghir, Gwichʼin, and Yupik.
[src:hypersaline-lake/arctic] The council operates on a consensus basis, mostly dealing with environmental treaties and not addressing boundary or resource disputes.
[src:hypersaline-lake/arctic] Though Arctic policy priorities differ, every Arctic nation is concerned about sovereignty/defense, resource development, shipping routes, and environmental protection.
[src:hypersaline-lake/arctic] Much work remains on regulatory agreements regarding shipping, tourism, and resource development in Arctic waters.
[src:hypersaline-lake/arctic] Arctic shipping is subject to some regulatory control through the International Code for Ships Operating in Polar Waters, adopted by the International Maritime Organization on 1 January 2017 and applies to all ships in Arctic waters over 500 tonnes.
[src:hypersaline-lake/arctic] Research in the Arctic has long been a collaborative international effort, evidenced by the International Polar Year.
[src:hypersaline-lake/arctic] The International Arctic Science Committee, hundreds of scientists and specialists of the Arctic Council, and the Barents Euro-Arctic Council are more examples of collaborative international Arctic research.
[src:hypersaline-lake/arctic] While there are several ongoing territorial claims in the Arctic, no country owns the geographic North Pole or the region of the Arctic Ocean surrounding it.
[src:hypersaline-lake/arctic] The surrounding six Arctic states that border the Arctic Ocean—Canada, the Kingdom of Denmark (with Greenland), Iceland, Norway, Russia, and the United States—are limited to a 200 nautical miles (370 km; 230 mi) exclusive economic zone (EEZ) off their coasts.
[src:hypersaline-lake/arctic] Two Arctic states (Finland and Sweden) do not have direct access to the Arctic Ocean.
[src:hypersaline-lake/arctic] Upon ratification of the United Nations Convention on the Law of the Sea, a country has ten years to make claims to an extended continental shelf beyond its 200 nautical mile zone.
[src:hypersaline-lake/arctic] Due to this, Norway (which ratified the convention in 1996), Russia (ratified in 1997), Canada (ratified in 2003) and the Kingdom of Denmark (ratified in 2004) launched projects to establish claims that certain sectors of the Arctic seabed should belong to their territories.
[src:hypersaline-lake/arctic] On 2 August 2007, two Russian bathyscaphes, MIR-1 and MIR-2, for the first time in history descended to the Arctic seabed beneath the North Pole and placed there a Russian flag made of rust-proof titanium alloy.
[src:hypersaline-lake/arctic] The flag-placing, during Arktika 2007, generated commentary on and concern for a race for control of the Arctic's vast hydrocarbon resources.
[src:hypersaline-lake/arctic] As of 2012, the Kingdom of Denmark is claiming the continental shelf based on the Lomonosov Ridge between Greenland and over the North Pole to the northern limit of the exclusive economic zone of Russia.
[src:hypersaline-lake/arctic] The Russian Federation is also claiming a large swath of seabed along the Lomonosov Ridge but, unlike Denmark, confined its claim to its side of the Arctic region.
[src:hypersaline-lake/arctic] In August 2015, Russia made a supplementary submission for the expansion of the external borders of its continental shelf in the Arctic Ocean, asserting that the eastern part of the Lomonosov Ridge and the Mendeleyev Ridge is an extension of the Eurasian continent.
[src:hypersaline-lake/arctic] In August 2016, the UN Commission on the Limits of the Continental Shelf began to consider Russia's submission.
[src:hypersaline-lake/arctic] Canada claims the Northwest Passage as part of its internal waters belonging to Canada, while the United States and most maritime nations regards it as an international strait, which means that foreign vessels have right of transit passage.
[src:hypersaline-lake/arctic] The Arctic is a site of strategic competition between world powers, particularly Russia and NATO.
[src:hypersaline-lake/arctic] Russia's Northern Fleet, stationed in the Kola Peninsula, is a major element of its nuclear deterrence strategy.
[src:hypersaline-lake/arctic] Russia also conducts nuclear weapons tests on Novaya Zemlya, and has sought to promote the use of the Northern Sea Route in international maritime trade.
[src:hypersaline-lake/arctic] The Trump administration has focused US attention on the Arctic, with Trump threatening to invade Greenland in 2025 and 2026, seeing direct control over it as essential to US strategic interests.
[src:hypersaline-lake/arctic] In response to Trump, the United States's NATO allies have sought to divert US attention toward Russian Arctic activities and bolster their own readiness.
[src:hypersaline-lake/arctic] Two strategically important straits in the Arctic are the GIUK Gap and the Bear Gap, between Svalbard and Norway.
[src:hypersaline-lake/arctic] Since 1937, the larger portion of the Asian-side Arctic region has been extensively explored by Soviet and Russian crewed drifting ice stations.
[src:hypersaline-lake/arctic] Between 1937 and 1991, 88 international polar crews established and occupied scientific settlements on the drift ice and were carried thousands of kilometers by the ice flow.
[src:hypersaline-lake/arctic] The Arctic is comparatively clean, although there are certain ecologically difficult localized pollution problems that present a serious threat to people's health living around these pollution sources.
[src:hypersaline-lake/arctic] Due to the prevailing worldwide sea and air currents, the Arctic area is the fallout region for long-range transport pollutants, and in some places, the concentrations exceed the levels of densely populated urban areas.
[src:hypersaline-lake/arctic] An example of this is the phenomenon of Arctic haze, which is commonly blamed on long-range pollutants.
[src:hypersaline-lake/arctic] Another example is with the bioaccumulation of PCBs (polychlorinated biphenyls) in Arctic wildlife and people.
[src:hypersaline-lake/arctic] There have been many proposals to preserve the Arctic over the years.
[src:hypersaline-lake/arctic] Most recently a group of states at the United Nations Conference on Sustainable Development, on 21 June 2012, proposed protecting the Arctic, similar to the Antarctic Treaty System.
[src:hypersaline-lake/arctic] The initial focus of the campaign will be a UN resolution creating a global sanctuary around the pole, and a ban on oil drilling and unsustainable fishing in the Arctic.
[src:hypersaline-lake/arctic] The Arctic has climate change rates that are amongst the highest in the world.
[src:hypersaline-lake/arctic] Due to the major impacts to the region from climate change the near climate future of the region will be extremely different under all scenarios of warming.
[src:hypersaline-lake/arctic] Decade-by-decade progression of arctic sea ice melting shows continued ice loss, with the greatest percentage loss rate experienced in the late summer and early autumn.
[src:hypersaline-lake/arctic] The area of Arctic sea ice reached a minimum in September 2012, but recent years have shown less area than 2012 in other months.
[src:hypersaline-lake/arctic] Late summer shows the greatest percentage loss.
[src:hypersaline-lake/arctic] The effects of climate change in the Arctic include rising temperatures, loss of sea ice, and melting of the Greenland ice sheet.
[src:hypersaline-lake/arctic] The Arctic near-surface temperature is increasing at a rate that is 2–3 times faster than the global average, which is referred to as Arctic amplification.
[src:hypersaline-lake/arctic] Potential methane release from the region, especially through the thawing of permafrost and methane clathrates, is also a concern.
[src:hypersaline-lake/arctic] Because of the amplified response of the Arctic to global warming, it is often seen as a leading indicator of global warming.
[src:hypersaline-lake/arctic] The Arctic region is especially vulnerable to the effects of any climate change, as has become apparent with the reduction of sea ice in recent years.
[src:hypersaline-lake/arctic] Climate models predict much greater climate change in the Arctic than the global average, resulting in significant international attention to the region.
[src:hypersaline-lake/arctic] In particular, there are concerns that Arctic shrinkage, a consequence of melting glaciers and other ice in Greenland, could soon contribute to a substantial rise in sea levels worldwide.
[src:hypersaline-lake/arctic] The current Arctic warming is leading to ancient carbon being released from thawing permafrost, leading to methane and carbon dioxide production by micro-organisms.
[src:hypersaline-lake/arctic] Release of methane and carbon dioxide stored in permafrost could cause abrupt and severe global warming, as they are potent greenhouse gases.
[src:hypersaline-lake/arctic] Climate change is also predicted to have a large impact on tundra vegetation, causing an increase of shrubs, and having a negative impact on bryophytes and lichens.
[src:hypersaline-lake/arctic] Apart from concerns regarding the detrimental effects of warming in the Arctic, some potential opportunities have gained attention.
[src:hypersaline-lake/arctic] The melting of the ice is making the Northwest Passage, shipping routes through the northernmost latitudes, more navigable, raising the possibility that the Arctic region will become a prime trade route.
[src:hypersaline-lake/arctic] One harbinger of the opening navigability of the Arctic took place in the summer of 2016 when the Crystal Serenity successfully navigated the Northwest Passage, a first for a large cruise ship.
[src:hypersaline-lake/arctic] In addition, it is believed that the Arctic seabed may contain substantial oil fields which may become accessible if the ice covering them melts.
[src:hypersaline-lake/arctic] These factors have led to recent international debates as to which nations can claim sovereignty or ownership over the waters of the Arctic.
[src:hypersaline-lake/arid] The distribution of aridity at any time is largely the result of the general circulation of the atmosphere.
[src:hypersaline-lake/arid] The latter does change significantly over time through climate change.
[src:hypersaline-lake/arid] For example, temperature increase by 1.5–2.1 percent across the Nile Basin over the next 30–40 years could change the region from semi-arid to arid, significantly reducing the land usable for agriculture.
[src:hypersaline-lake/arid] In addition, changes in land use can increase demands on soil water and thereby increase aridity.
[src:hypersaline-lake/body-of-water] A **body of water** or **waterbody** is any significant accumulation of water on the surface of the earth.
[src:hypersaline-lake/body-of-water] The term most often refers to oceans, seas, and lakes, but it includes smaller pools of water such as ponds, wetlands, or more rarely, puddles.
[src:hypersaline-lake/body-of-water] A body of water does not have to be still or contained; rivers, streams, canals, and other geographical features where water moves from one place to another are also considered bodies of water.
[src:hypersaline-lake/body-of-water] Most are naturally occurring and massive geographical features, but some are artificial.
[src:hypersaline-lake/body-of-water] For example, most reservoirs are created by engineering dams, but some natural lakes are used as reservoirs.
[src:hypersaline-lake/body-of-water] Similarly, most harbors are naturally occurring bays, but some harbors have been created through construction.
[src:hypersaline-lake/body-of-water] Bodies of water that are navigable are known as waterways.
[src:hypersaline-lake/body-of-water] Some bodies of water collect and move water, such as rivers and streams, and others primarily hold water, such as lakes and oceans.
[src:hypersaline-lake/body-of-water] Bodies of water are affected by gravity, which is what creates the tidal effects.
[src:hypersaline-lake/body-of-water] The impact of climate change on water is likely to intensify as observed through the rising sea levels, water acidification and flooding.
[src:hypersaline-lake/body-of-water] This means that climate change has pressure on water bodies.
[src:hypersaline-lake/body-of-water] Climate change significantly affects bodies of water through rising temperatures, altered precipitation patterns, and sea-level rise.
[src:hypersaline-lake/body-of-water] Warmer temperatures lead to the melting of glaciers and polar ice, contributing to rising sea levels and affecting coastal ecosystems.
[src:hypersaline-lake/body-of-water] Freshwater bodies, such as rivers and lakes, are experiencing more frequent droughts, affecting water availability for communities and biodiversity.
[src:hypersaline-lake/body-of-water] Moreover, ocean acidification, caused by increased carbon dioxide absorption, threatens marine ecosystems like coral reefs.
[src:hypersaline-lake/body-of-water] Collaborative global efforts are needed to mitigate these impacts through sustainable water management practices.
[src:hypersaline-lake/body-of-water] This is a list of some common types of bodies of water.
[src:hypersaline-lake/body-of-water] Some common geographical features involving water are not bodies of water in their own right, such as geysers, rapids, and waterfalls, and are therefore not included on this list.
[src:hypersaline-lake/body-of-water] Some terms, particularly relating to wetlands, refer in part to one or more bodies of water and in part to the land surrounding them, and these have been included on this list.
[src:hypersaline-lake/body-of-water] , one of the major water-traffic corridors in the city.
[src:hypersaline-lake/body-of-water] Weirs are frequently used to change the height of a riverlevel, prevent floodings, and measure water discharge.
[src:hypersaline-lake/brackish-water] Technically, brackish water contains between 0.5 and 30 grams of salt per litre—more often expressed as 0.5 to 30 parts per thousand (‰), which is a specific gravity of between 1.0004 and 1.0226.
[src:hypersaline-lake/brackish-water] Thus, *brackish* covers a range of salinity regimes and is not considered a precisely defined condition.
[src:hypersaline-lake/brackish-water] It is characteristic of many brackish surface waters that their salinity can vary considerably over space or time.
[src:hypersaline-lake/brackish-water] Water with a salt concentration greater than 30‰ is considered saline.
[src:hypersaline-lake/brackish-water] Brackish water condition commonly occurs when fresh water meets seawater.
[src:hypersaline-lake/brackish-water] In fact, the most extensive brackish water habitats worldwide are estuaries, where a river meets the sea.
[src:hypersaline-lake/brackish-water] The River Thames flowing through London is a classic river estuary.
[src:hypersaline-lake/brackish-water] The Thames Estuary becomes brackish between Battersea and Gravesend, and the diversity of freshwater fish species present is smaller, primarily roach and dace; euryhaline marine species such as flounder, European seabass, mullet, and smelt become much more common.
[src:hypersaline-lake/brackish-water] A similar pattern of replacement can be observed with the aquatic plants and invertebrates living in the river.
[src:hypersaline-lake/brackish-water] This type of ecological succession from freshwater to marine ecosystem is typical of river estuaries.
[src:hypersaline-lake/brackish-water] River estuaries form important staging points during the migration of anadromous and catadromous fish species, such as salmon, shad and eels, giving them time to form social groups and to adjust to the changes in salinity.
[src:hypersaline-lake/brackish-water] Salmon are anadromous, meaning they live in the sea but ascend rivers to spawn; eels are catadromous, living in rivers and streams, but returning to the sea to breed.
[src:hypersaline-lake/brackish-water] Besides the species that migrate through estuaries, there are many other fish that use them as "nursery grounds" for spawning or as places young fish can feed and grow before moving elsewhere.
[src:hypersaline-lake/brackish-water] Herring and plaice are two commercially important species that use the Thames Estuary for this purpose.
[src:hypersaline-lake/brackish-water] Estuaries are also commonly used as fishing grounds and as places for fish farming or ranching.
[src:hypersaline-lake/brackish-water] For example, Atlantic salmon farms are often located in estuaries, although this has caused controversy, because in doing so, fish farmers expose migrating wild fish to large numbers of external parasites such as sea lice that escape from the pens the farmed fish are kept in.
[src:hypersaline-lake/brackish-water] Another important brackish water habitat is the mangrove swamp or mangal.
[src:hypersaline-lake/brackish-water] Many, though not all, mangrove swamps fringe estuaries and lagoons where the salinity changes with each tide.
[src:hypersaline-lake/brackish-water] Among the most specialised residents of mangrove forests are mudskippers, fish that forage for food on land, and archerfish, perch-like fish that "spit" at insects and other small animals living in the trees, knocking them into the water where they can be eaten.
[src:hypersaline-lake/brackish-water] Like estuaries, mangrove swamps are extremely important breeding grounds for many fish, with species such as snappers, halfbeaks, and tarpon spawning or maturing among them.
[src:hypersaline-lake/brackish-water] Besides fish, numerous other animals use mangroves, including such species as the saltwater crocodile, American crocodile, proboscis monkey, diamondback terrapin, and the crab-eating frog, *Fejervarya cancrivora* (formerly *Rana cancrivora*).
[src:hypersaline-lake/brackish-water] Mangroves represent important nesting sites for numerous birds groups such as herons, storks, spoonbills, ibises, kingfishers, shorebirds and seabirds.
[src:hypersaline-lake/brackish-water] Although often plagued with mosquitoes and other insects that make them unpleasant for humans, mangrove swamps are very important buffer zones between land and sea, and are a natural defense against hurricane and tsunami damage in particular.
[src:hypersaline-lake/brackish-water] The Sundarbans and Bhitarkanika Mangroves are two of the large mangrove forests in the world, both on the coast of the Bay of Bengal.
[src:hypersaline-lake/brackish-water] The Baltic Sea is a brackish sea adjoining the North Sea.
[src:hypersaline-lake/brackish-water] Originally the Eridanos river system prior to the Pleistocene, since then it has been flooded by the North Sea but still receives so much freshwater from the adjacent lands that the water is brackish.
[src:hypersaline-lake/brackish-water] As seawater is denser, the water in the Baltic is stratified, with seawater at the bottom and freshwater at the top.
[src:hypersaline-lake/brackish-water] Limited mixing occurs because of the lack of tides and storms, with the result that the fish fauna at the surface is freshwater in composition while that lower down is more marine.
[src:hypersaline-lake/brackish-water] Cod are an example of a species only found in deep water in the Baltic, while pike are confined to the less saline surface waters.
[src:hypersaline-lake/brackish-water] The Caspian Sea is the world's largest lake and contains brackish water with a salinity about one-third that of normal seawater.
[src:hypersaline-lake/brackish-water] The Caspian is famous for its peculiar animal fauna, including one of the few non-marine seals (the Caspian seal) and the great sturgeons, a major source of caviar.
[src:hypersaline-lake/brackish-water] In the Black Sea the surface water is brackish with an average salinity of about 17–18 parts per thousand compared to 30 to 40 for the oceans.
[src:hypersaline-lake/brackish-water] The deep, anoxic water of the Black Sea originates from warm, salty water of the Mediterranean.
[src:hypersaline-lake/brackish-water] Lake Texoma, a reservoir on the border between the U.S. states of Texas and Oklahoma, is a rare example of a brackish lake that is neither part of an endorheic basin nor a direct arm of the ocean, though its salinity is considerably lower than that of the other bodies of water mentioned here.
[src:hypersaline-lake/brackish-water] The reservoir was created by the damming of the Red River of the South, which (along with several of its tributaries) receives large amounts of salt from natural seepage from buried deposits in the upstream region.
[src:hypersaline-lake/brackish-water] The salinity is high enough that striped bass, a fish normally found only in salt water, has self-sustaining populations in the lake.
[src:hypersaline-lake/brackish-water] Brackish marshes develop from salt marshes where a significant freshwater influx dilutes the seawater to brackish levels of salinity.
[src:hypersaline-lake/brackish-water] This commonly happens upstream from salt marshes by estuaries of coastal rivers or near the mouths of coastal rivers with heavy freshwater discharges in the conditions of low tidal ranges.
[src:hypersaline-lake/brackish-water] Brackish water is used by humans in many different sectors.
[src:hypersaline-lake/brackish-water] It is commonly used as cooling water for power generation and in a variety of ways in the mining, oil, and gas industries.
[src:hypersaline-lake/brackish-water] Once desalinated it can also be used for agriculture, livestock, and municipal uses.
[src:hypersaline-lake/brackish-water] Brackish water can be treated using reverse osmosis, electrodialysis, and other filtration processes.
[src:hypersaline-lake/brine] Brines are produced in multiple ways in nature.
[src:hypersaline-lake/brine] Modification of seawater via evaporation results in the concentration of salts in the residual fluid, a characteristic geologic deposit called an evaporite is formed as different dissolved ions reach the saturation states of minerals, typically gypsum and halite.
[src:hypersaline-lake/brine] Dissolution of such salt deposits into water can produce brines as well.
[src:hypersaline-lake/brine] As seawater freezes, dissolved ions tend to remain in solution resulting in a fluid termed a cryogenic brine.
[src:hypersaline-lake/brine] At the time of formation, these cryogenic brines are by definition cooler than the freezing temperature of seawater and can produce a feature called a brinicle where cool brines descend, freezing the surrounding seawater.
[src:hypersaline-lake/brine] The brine cropping out at the surface as saltwater springs are known as "licks" or "salines".
[src:hypersaline-lake/brine] The contents of dissolved solids in groundwater vary highly from one location to another on Earth, both in terms of specific constituents (e.g., halite, anhydrite, carbonates, gypsum, fluoride-salts, organic halides, and sulfate-salts) and regarding the concentration level.
[src:hypersaline-lake/brine] Using one of several classification of groundwater based on total dissolved solids (TDS), brine is water containing more than 100,000 mg/L TDS.
[src:hypersaline-lake/brine] Brine is commonly produced during well completion operations, particularly after the hydraulic fracturing of a well.
[src:hypersaline-lake/brine] Iodine, essential for human health, is obtained on a commercial scale from iodide-rich brines.
[src:hypersaline-lake/brine] The purification begins by converting iodide to hydroiodic acid, which is then oxidized to iodine using chlorine.
[src:hypersaline-lake/brine] The iodine is then separated by evaporation or adsorption.
[src:hypersaline-lake/brine] Akin to the production of iodine, the process exploits the easy oxidation of bromide into bromine, again using chlorine as the oxidant.
[src:hypersaline-lake/brine] The product bromine can be selectively collected by exploiting its volatility.
[src:hypersaline-lake/brine] Major deposits of lithium are in the form of brines.
[src:hypersaline-lake/brine] Magnesium is also produced in part from waste brine from various sources, such as potash production.
[src:hypersaline-lake/brine] Crude magnesium oxides and chlorides mixtures are converted into magnesium metal by electrolysis.
[src:hypersaline-lake/brine] Elemental chlorine can be produced by electrolysis of brine (NaCl solution).
[src:hypersaline-lake/brine] This process also produces sodium hydroxide (NaOH) and hydrogen gas (H2).
[src:hypersaline-lake/brine] Brine (primarily cheap brines based on calcium chloride and sodium chloride) is used as a secondary fluid in large refrigeration installations to transport thermal energy.
[src:hypersaline-lake/brine] It is used because the addition of salt to water lowers the freezing temperature of the solution, significantly enhancing its heat transport efficiency at low cost.
[src:hypersaline-lake/brine] The lowest freezing point obtainable for NaCl brine (called its eutectic point) is −21.1 °C (−6.0 °F) at the concentration of 23.3% NaCl by weight.
[src:hypersaline-lake/brine] Because of their corrosive properties, salt-based brines have been replaced by organic liquids such as ethylene glycol.
[src:hypersaline-lake/brine] Sodium chloride brine spray is used on some fishing vessels to freeze fish.
[src:hypersaline-lake/brine] The brine temperature is generally −5 °F (−21 °C).
[src:hypersaline-lake/brine] Air blast freezing temperatures are −31 °F (−35 °C) or lower.
[src:hypersaline-lake/brine] Given the higher temperature of brine, the system efficiency over air blast freezing can be higher.
[src:hypersaline-lake/brine] High-value fish usually are frozen at much lower temperatures, below the practical temperature limit for brine.
[src:hypersaline-lake/brine] Brine is used for regeneration of ion-exchange resins.
[src:hypersaline-lake/brine] After treatment, ion-exchange resin beads saturated with calcium and magnesium ions from the treated water, are regenerated by soaking in brine containing 6–12% NaCl.
[src:hypersaline-lake/brine] The sodium ions from brine replace the calcium and magnesium ions on the beads.
[src:hypersaline-lake/brine] Brine is a common agent in food processing and cooking.
[src:hypersaline-lake/brine] Brining is used to preserve or season the food.
[src:hypersaline-lake/brine] Brining can be applied to vegetables, cheeses, fruit, and some fish in a process known as pickling.
[src:hypersaline-lake/brine] Meat and fish are typically steeped in brine for shorter periods of time, as a form of marination, enhancing its tenderness and flavor, or to enhance shelf period.
[src:hypersaline-lake/brine] In lower temperatures, a brine solution can be used to de-ice or reduce freezing temperatures on roads.
[src:hypersaline-lake/brine] Quenching is a heat-treatment process when forging metals such as steel.
[src:hypersaline-lake/brine] A brine solution, along with oil and other substances, is commonly used to harden steel.
[src:hypersaline-lake/brine] When brine is used, there is an enhanced uniformity of the cooling process and heat transfer.
[src:hypersaline-lake/brine] The desalination process consists of the separation of salts from an aqueous solution to obtain fresh water from a source of seawater or brackish water; and in turn, a discharge is generated, commonly called brine.
[src:hypersaline-lake/brine] The characteristics of the discharge depend on different factors, such as the desalination technology used, salinity and quality of the water used, environmental and oceanographic characteristics, desalination process carried out, among others.
[src:hypersaline-lake/brine] The discharge could contain trace chemical products used during the industrial treatments applies, such as antiscalants, coagulants, flocculants which are discarded together with the discharge, and those which could affect the physical-chemical quality of the effluent.
[src:hypersaline-lake/brine] However, these are practically consumed during the process and the concentrations in the discharge are very low, which are practically diluted during the discharge, without affecting marine ecosystems.
[src:hypersaline-lake/brine] The materials used in SWRO plants are dominated by non-metallic components and stainless steels, since lower operating temperatures allow the construction of desalination plants with more corrosion-resistant coatings.
[src:hypersaline-lake/brine] Therefore, the concentration values of heavy metals in the discharge of SWRO plants are much lower than the acute toxicity levels to generate environmental impacts on marine ecosystems.
[src:hypersaline-lake/brine] The discharge is generally dumped back into the sea, through an underwater outfall or coastal release, due to its lower energy and economic cost compared to other discharge methods.
[src:hypersaline-lake/brine] Due to its increase in salinity, the discharge has a greater density compared to the surrounding seawater.
[src:hypersaline-lake/brine] Therefore, when the discharge reaches the sea, it can form a saline plume that tends to follow the bathymetric line of the bottom until it is completely diluted.
[src:hypersaline-lake/brine] The distribution of the salt plume may depend on different factors, such as the production capacity of the plant, the discharge method, the oceanographic and environmental conditions of the discharge point, among others.
[src:hypersaline-lake/brine] Brine discharge might lead to an increase in salinity above certain threshold levels that has the potential to affect benthic communities, especially those more sensitive to osmotic pressure, finally having an effect on their abundance and diversity.
[src:hypersaline-lake/brine] However, if appropriate mitigation measures are applied, the potential environmental impacts of discharges from SWRO plants can be correctly minimized.
[src:hypersaline-lake/brine] Some examples can be found in countries such as Spain, Israel, Chile or Australia, in which the mitigation measures adopted reduce the area affected by the discharge, guaranteeing a sustainable development of the desalination process without significant impacts on marine ecosystems.
[src:hypersaline-lake/brine] When noticeable effects have been detected on the environment surrounding discharge areas, it generally corresponds to old desalination plants in which the correct mitigation measures were not implemented.
[src:hypersaline-lake/brine] Some examples can be found in Spain, Australia or Chile, where it has been shown that saline plumes do not exceed values of 5% with respect to the natural salinity of the sea in a radius less than 100 m from the point of discharge when proper measures are adopted.
[src:hypersaline-lake/brine] Currently, in many countries, such as Spain, Israel, Chile, and Australia, the development of a rigorous environmental impact assessment process is required, both for the construction and operational phases.
[src:hypersaline-lake/brine] During its development, the most important legal management tools are established within the local environmental regulation, to prevent and adopt mitigation measures that guarantee the sustainable development of desalination projects.
[src:hypersaline-lake/brine] This includes a series of administrative tools and periodic environmental monitoring, to adopt preventive, corrective and further monitoring measures of the state of the surrounding marine environment.
[src:hypersaline-lake/brine] The PVAs establishes a series of mandatory requirements that are mainly related to the monitoring of discharge, using a series of measurements and characterizations based on physical-chemical and biological information.
[src:hypersaline-lake/brine] In addition, the PVAs could include different requirements related to monitoring the effects of seawater intake and those that may potentially be related to effects on the terrestrial environment.
[src:hypersaline-lake/brine] Along with diluted salts, it can contain residues of pretreatment and cleaning chemicals, their reaction byproducts and heavy metals due to corrosion.
[src:hypersaline-lake/brine] Wastewater brine can pose a significant environmental hazard, both due to corrosive and sediment-forming effects of salts and toxicity of other chemicals diluted in it.
[src:hypersaline-lake/brine] Unpolluted brine from desalination plants and cooling towers can be returned to the ocean.
[src:hypersaline-lake/brine] From the desalination process, reject brine is produced, which may damage marine life and habitats.
[src:hypersaline-lake/brine] To limit the environmental impact, it can be diluted with another stream of water, such as the outfall of a wastewater treatment or power plant.
[src:hypersaline-lake/brine] Since brine is heavier than seawater and would accumulate on the ocean bottom, it requires methods to ensure proper diffusion, such as installing underwater diffusers in the sewerage.
[src:hypersaline-lake/brine] Other methods include drying in evaporation ponds, injecting to deep wells, and storing and reusing the brine for irrigation, de-icing or dust control purposes.
[src:hypersaline-lake/brine] New methods for membrane brine concentration, employing osmotically assisted reverse osmosis and related processes, are beginning to gain ground as part of zero liquid discharge systems (ZLD).
[src:hypersaline-lake/brine] Brine consists of concentrated solution of Na+ and Cl− ions.
[src:hypersaline-lake/brine] Other cations found in various brines include K+, Mg2+, Ca2+, and Sr2+.
[src:hypersaline-lake/brine] The latter three are problematic because they form scale and they react with soaps.
[src:hypersaline-lake/brine] Aside from chloride, brines sometimes contain Br− and I− and, most problematically, sulfate SO2− 4.
[src:hypersaline-lake/brine] Purification steps often include the addition of calcium oxide to precipitate solid magnesium hydroxide together with gypsum (CaSO4), which can be removed by filtration.
[src:hypersaline-lake/brine] Further purification is achieved by fractional crystallization.
[src:hypersaline-lake/brine] The resulting purified salt is called **evaporated salt** or **vacuum salt**.
[src:hypersaline-lake/hypersaline-lake] A **hypersaline lake** is a landlocked body of water that contains significant concentrations of sodium chloride, brines, and other salts, with saline levels surpassing those of ocean water (3.5%, i.e.
[src:hypersaline-lake/hypersaline-lake] 35 grams per litre or 0.29 pounds per US gallon).
[src:hypersaline-lake/hypersaline-lake] Specific microbial species can thrive in high-salinity environments that are inhospitable to most lifeforms, including some that are thought to contribute to the color of pink lakes.
[src:hypersaline-lake/hypersaline-lake] Some of these species enter a dormant state when desiccated, and some species are thought to survive for over 250 million years.
[src:hypersaline-lake/hypersaline-lake] The water in hypersaline lakes has great buoyancy due to its high salt content.
[src:hypersaline-lake/hypersaline-lake] Hypersaline lakes are found on every continent, especially in arid or semi-arid regions.
[src:hypersaline-lake/hypersaline-lake] In the Arctic, the Canadian Devon Ice Cap contains two subglacial lakes that are hypersaline.
[src:hypersaline-lake/hypersaline-lake] In Antarctica, there are larger hypersaline water bodies, lakes in the McMurdo Dry Valleys such as Lake Vanda with salinity of over 35% (i.e.
[src:hypersaline-lake/hypersaline-lake] The most saline water body in the world is the Gaet'ale Pond, located in the Danakil Depression in Afar, Ethiopia.
[src:hypersaline-lake/hypersaline-lake] The water of Gaet'ale Pond has a salinity of 43%, making it the saltiest water body on Earth (i.e.
[src:hypersaline-lake/hypersaline-lake] Previously, it was considered that the most saline lake outside of Antarctica was Lake Assal, in Djibouti, which has a salinity of 34.8% (i.e.
[src:hypersaline-lake/hypersaline-lake] The best-known hypersaline lakes are the Dead Sea (34.2% salinity in 2010) and the Great Salt Lake in the state of Utah, US (5–27% variable salinity).
[src:hypersaline-lake/hypersaline-lake] The Dead Sea, dividing Israel and the West Bank from Jordan, is the world's deepest hypersaline lake.
[src:hypersaline-lake/hypersaline-lake] The Great Salt Lake, while having nearly three times the surface area of the Dead Sea, is shallower and experiences much greater fluctuations in salinity.
[src:hypersaline-lake/hypersaline-lake] At its lowest recorded water levels, it approaches 7.7 times the salinity of ocean water, but when its levels are high, its salinity drops to only slightly higher than that of the ocean.
